<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920310-0068</DOCNO><DOCID>920310-0068.</DOCID><HL>   Technology Brief-- WordStar International Inc.:   Negotiations With Delrina   Focus on Possible Merger</HL><DATE>03/10/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10</SO><CO>   T.DC WDST</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)SOFTWARE (SOF)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS, MERGERS, TAKEOVERS (TNM)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)CANADA (CN)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WordStar International Inc., Novato, Calif., said it isnegotiating a possible merger with software publisher DelrinaCorp., Toronto, Canada.   David Russian, WordStar's chief financial officer, said noagreement has been reached on the terms of any suchtransaction, which would happen through an exchange of stock.Neither of the companies has approved any transaction, and noagreement or letters of intent have been signed, he said. Nodecision has been reached on which company would be thesurviving party, Mr. Russian added.</LP><TEXT>   Delrina's products, including software to handle facsimiletransmissions and to generate forms, would complimentWordStar's main product, a word-processing program forpersonal computers, Mr. Russian said. A merger between thecompanies &quot;would be a strategic fit because of our productlines,&quot; he said.</TEXT></DOC>